## Setup tutorial

### 1. Install xxh

```sh
pipx install xxh-xxh
```

### 2. Install the fish shell plugin

```sh
xxh +I xxh-shell-fish
```

### 3. Create the ssh-wrapper

Required because xxh's built-in rsync command conflicts with SSH ControlMaster multiplexing. Even though we use SCP for uploads, the wrapper is kept in case rsync is ever used.

```sh
mkdir -p ~/.xxh
cat > ~/.xxh/ssh-wrapper.sh << 'EOF'
#!/bin/bash
exec ssh -o ControlMaster=no -o ControlPath=none "$@"
EOF
chmod +x ~/.xxh/ssh-wrapper.sh
```

### 4. Stage the Linux static binaries

Download static Linux x86-64 builds and place them in `~/.xxh/bin/`:

```sh
mkdir -p ~/.xxh/bin
# download starship-x86_64-unknown-linux-musl.tar.gz from github.com/starship/starship/releases
# download fzf-*-linux_amd64.tar.gz from github.com/junegunn/fzf/releases
# download atuin-x86_64-unknown-linux-musl.tar.gz from github.com/atuinsh/atuin/releases
chmod +x ~/.xxh/bin/starship ~/.xxh/bin/fzf ~/.xxh/bin/atuin
```

### 5. Write the xxh config

`~/.config/xxh/config.xxhc`:

```yaml
hosts:
  ".*":
    +s: xxh-shell-fish
    ++pexpect-timeout: "30"
    ++copy-method: scp
    +if:
    +hhh: "~"
    +hhr:
    -o:
      - ControlMaster=no
      - ControlPath=none
```

| Option | Effect |
|---|---|
| `+s: xxh-shell-fish` | Use the portable fish shell plugin |
| `++pexpect-timeout: "30"` | Allow 30 s for slow hosts to respond during handshake |
| `++copy-method: scp` | Use SCP instead of rsync (rsync has a flag conflict in this setup) |
| `+if:` | Always install without prompting — needed because `+hhr` wipes the remote on every disconnect, so xxh would otherwise ask "Install? [Y/n]" on every connect |
| `+hhh: "~"` | Set `HOME` to your real home on the remote, not `~/.xxh` |
| `+hhr:` | Delete `~/.xxh` on the remote after disconnect (zero footprint) |
| `-o ControlMaster=no` | Prevent SSH multiplexing conflicts |

### 6. Stage starship into the fish build dir

```sh
mkdir -p ~/.xxh/.xxh/shells/xxh-shell-fish/build/bin
cp ~/.config/starship.toml ~/.xxh/.xxh/shells/xxh-shell-fish/build/starship.toml
cp ~/.xxh/bin/starship     ~/.xxh/.xxh/shells/xxh-shell-fish/build/bin/starship
chmod +x ~/.xxh/.xxh/shells/xxh-shell-fish/build/bin/starship
```

### 7. Wire starship into the fish session config

Edit `~/.xxh/.xxh/shells/xxh-shell-fish/build/xxh-config.fish` — add before the final `cd ~`:

```fish
if test -f $CURRENT_DIR/bin/starship
    set -x PATH $CURRENT_DIR/bin $PATH
    set -x STARSHIP_CONFIG $CURRENT_DIR/starship.toml
    starship init fish | source
end
```

`$CURRENT_DIR` is set by xxh-config.fish itself to the build directory path on the remote, so these paths resolve correctly regardless of username.

### 8. Add the connect wrapper to local fish

`~/.config/fish/functions/xxhc.fish`:

```fish
function xxhc --description "xxh with SSH alias forwarded to remote prompt"
    set -l target $argv[1]
    env RSYNC_RSH=~/.xxh/ssh-wrapper.sh xxh $target +e "XXH_SSH_ALIAS=$target" $argv[2..-1]
end
```

This does three things: sets `RSYNC_RSH` so rsync bypasses ControlMaster, passes the SSH alias as `XXH_SSH_ALIAS` so starship can display it in the prompt, and forwards any extra xxh flags you add after the hostname.

### 9. Configure starship

`~/.config/starship.toml` — applies both to the local Mac prompt and the remote session (via the copy in the build dir):

```toml
format = """
$username$hostname${env_var.XXH_SSH_ALIAS}$directory$git_branch$git_status
$character"""

[username]
show_always = false
style_user = "green bold"
format = "[$user]($style)"

[hostname]
ssh_only = true
format = "[ @ $hostname]($style) "
style = "yellow bold"

[directory]
truncation_length = 3

[git_branch]
format = "[$symbol$branch]($style) "
style = "cyan"

[env_var.XXH_SSH_ALIAS]
variable = "XXH_SSH_ALIAS"
format = "\\([$env_value]($style)\\) "
style = "blue bold"

[character]
success_symbol = "[›](green)"
error_symbol = "[›](red)"
```

`hostname` uses `ssh_only = true` so it only shows on remote sessions. `env_var.XXH_SSH_ALIAS` only renders when the variable is set, which only happens via `xxhc`. On the local Mac neither appears.

After saving, sync to the build dir:

```sh
cp ~/.config/starship.toml ~/.xxh/.xxh/shells/xxh-shell-fish/build/starship.toml
```

### 10. Local fish config

`~/.config/fish/config.fish` — initialises the local Mac environment:

```fish
starship init fish | source
fzf --fish | source
atuin init fish --disable-up-arrow | source
```

This is unrelated to the remote setup — it's just the local Mac prompt and tooling.

